Exploring a data set of fossil occurrences in R

Fossil Occurrences

The data set below contains information about the first and last appearance for each unique species in the family Canidae that is represented in the PBDB.

library(ggplot2)
## Warning: package 'ggplot2' was built under R version 3.3.2
setwd("/Users/michael_alfaro/Dropbox/teaching/EEB 177:234 2016/range-plotting/") #you will need to change this to match your directory!
canids <- read.csv("/Users/michael_alfaro/Dropbox/teaching/EEB 177:234 2016/range-plotting/canid_fa_la.csv", header = F, as.is = T)
names(canids) <- c("genus", "species", "minage", "maxage")
head(canids)
##       genus                 species minage maxage
## 1 Aelurodon Aelurodon_asthenostylus  15.97  20.43
## 2 Aelurodon         Aelurodon_ferox  13.60  23.03
## 3 Aelurodon       Aelurodon_mcgrewi  15.97  23.03
## 4 Aelurodon   Aelurodon_montanensis  15.97  15.97
## 5 Aelurodon      Aelurodon_stirtoni  13.60  23.03
## 6 Aelurodon      Aelurodon_taxoides  10.30  23.03
canid_occ <- ggplot(canids, aes( species, ymin = maxage, ymax=minage, colour = genus))
canid_occ <- canid_occ + geom_linerange()
canid_occ

The legend is obscuring most of the plot. We can remove it with the theme argument.

canid_occ <- canid_occ + theme(legend.position="none")
canid_occ

These plots are traditionally shown with the ranges as horizontal. We can flip the axis with coord_flip().

canid_occ <- canid_occ + coord_flip()
canid_occ

The species names are too large. Lets try making them smaller.

canid_occ <- canid_occ +  theme(axis.text.y = element_text(size=3))
canid_occ

Lets get rid of the tick marks on the y axis.

canid_occ <- canid_occ + theme(axis.ticks.y=element_blank())
canid_occ

Lets set the x range on the plot so that we dont have as much empty space on the right or left.

canid_occ <- canid_occ + scale_y_continuous(limits=c(0, 40), expand = c(0, 0), breaks=c(0, 10, 20, 30, 40))
canid_occ
## Warning: Removed 3 rows containing missing values (geom_linerange).

Now lets add a title to the plot and modify the x and y labels

canid_occ <- canid_occ + labs(title = "Canid Fossil Occurrences", x = "Species", y = "Ma ago") + theme(plot.title = element_text(hjust = 0.5, size=22, face = "bold"), axis.title =element_text(size=20))
canid_occ
## Warning: Removed 3 rows containing missing values (geom_linerange).

We can save this figure with ggsave.

ggsave(filename = "canid-occ.pdf", plot = canid_occ)
## Saving 7 x 5 in image
## Warning: Removed 3 rows containing missing values (geom_linerange).

Now lets explore an R package designed for analyzing stratigraphic occurrence data.
